on volumes — the books of this era, printed before 1501, are known as incunabula, from the Latin for \"cradle.\"\n\n## The Print Revolution\n\nThe consequences unfolded quickly and unpredictably. In Venice, Aldus Manutius pioneered the compact, affordable octavo edition and italic type, making the classics portable. Printed indulgences and pamphlets became a lucrative trade — and it was precisely this trade that Martin Luther exploited in 1517. His Ninety-Five Theses spread across Germany in weeks, and Luther became arguably the first mass-media author; without the press, the Reformation might have been suppressed as earlier heresies had been. The Catholic Church responded with its own printed polemics and, eventually, the Index of Forbidden Books — an acknowledgment that print had created a battlefield of ideas no authority could fully police.\n\nScience was transformed as well. Print allowed exact reproduction of diagrams, tables, and mathematical notation, so that scholars in different countries could scrutinize identical texts. Copernicus, Vesalius, and later Newton published into a scholarly network that print had made possible. Standardized editions stabilized languages themselves: printers' choices helped fix the spelling and grammar of vernacular tongues, nudging Europe from a Latin-speaking learned elite toward national reading publics. Literacy rates climbed steadily as books, broadsides, and eventually newspapers became affordable.\n\n## Industrialization and Legacy\n\nFor three and a half centuries, printing technology changed remarkably little — Benjamin Franklin's press would have been familiar to Gutenberg. The nineteenth century broke that stasis. Friedrich Koenig's steam-powered cylinder press, first used by The Times of London in 1814, multiplied output tenfold. Richard Hoe's rotary press, printing on continuous rolls of cheap wood-pulp paper, made the penny newspaper possible. Ottmar Mergenthaler's Linotype machine of 1884 mechanized typesetting itself, casting whole lines of type at the touch of a keyboard. Print became truly mass media, feeding an industrial society hungry for news, fiction, and advertising.\n\nThe twentieth century brought offset lithography and phototypesetting, and finally digital composition, which retired hot metal type by the 1980s. Yet even as screens displace paper, the press's legacy is everywhere: in the very idea of a reading public, of authorship and copyright, of standardized knowledge available to anyone. Gutenberg's machine democratized memory itself — and every technology of information since, from the telegraph to the internet, has been in some sense an elaboration of the revolution that began in a Mainz workshop nearly six centuries ago.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"039fcd25-696f-471c-9908-214ee2c9c292","total_cost_usd":0.32916049999999997,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3140,"cache_read_input_tokens":18449,"output_tokens":2130,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3140,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2130,"cache_read_input_tokens":18449,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3140,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3140},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":536,"outputTokens":12,"cacheReadInputTokens":0,"cacheCreationInputTokens":0,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.0005960000000000001,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-fable-5":{"inputTokens":3654,"outputTokens":2274,"cacheReadInputTokens":76887,"cacheCreationInputTokens":6231,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.3285645,"contextWindow":1000000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"b73f74cc-170e-4316-81cc-aba02fb962f1"}
